# APPENDIX A: PROOF OF THEOREM 2.1 

Given some fixed constant $f_{\min }>0$, recall the definition of the parameter space $\mathcal{F}$ in (2.1), and the notation $\mathcal{L}_{f}[\cdot]=\nabla \cdot(f \nabla[\cdot])$ for the infinitesimal generator of $\left(X_{t}, t \geq 0\right)$, with domain

$$
\mathcal{D}\left(\mathcal{L}_{f}\right)=H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})=\left\{u \in H^{2}(\mathcal{O}): \partial_{\nu} u=0 \text { on } \partial \mathcal{O}\right\}
$$

equipped with the $H^{2}(\mathcal{O})$-norm. Moreover, let $\varphi_{t}(x, y), x, y \in \mathcal{O}$, and $\left(P_{t, 0}, t \geq 0\right)$ respectively denote the transition densities and the transition semigroup of the reflected Brownian motion on $\mathcal{O}$,

$$
d Y_{t}=\sqrt{2} d W_{t}+\nu\left(Y_{t}\right) d L_{t}, \quad t \geq 0
$$

A.1. Proof strategy. In order to prove the gradient characterisation stated in Theorem 2.1, we first introduce a sequence of regularised transition densities $p_{t, f}^{\delta}$ that are shown to satisfy certain parabolic PDEs whose initial conditions become singular as $\delta \rightarrow 0$ (Section A.2). For each fixed $\delta>0$, we then use the regularity theory for parabolic PDEs (reviewed in Section A.3) to estimate the differences between the regularised transition densities (Section A.4). Using a recursive argument, higher order differences can also be controlled (Section A.5). Finally, the result is obtained by employing a careful limiting argument to let the regularisation parameter $\delta \rightarrow 0$ (Section A.6).
A.2. Regularised transition densities. For any conductivity function $f \in \mathcal{F}$, we define a regularised version of the transition density $p_{t, f}$ by

$$
p_{t, f}^{\delta}(x, y):=P_{t, f}\left[\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right](x)=P_{\delta, 0}\left[p_{t, f}(x, \cdot)\right](y), \quad t, \delta>0, \quad x, y \in \mathcal{O}
$$

It will be helpful to regard these as functions from $[0, T]$ to $L^{2}(\mathcal{O})$ for some $T>0$, where $y$ is fixed and the space variable is $x$. To this end, we introduce the notation

$$
u_{f}^{\delta}(t):=p_{t, f}^{\delta}(\cdot, y), \quad u_{f}^{\delta}:[0, T] \rightarrow L^{2}(\mathcal{O})
$$

By standard parabolic PDE theory (see [59, Proposition 4.1.2]), it is clear that $u_{f}^{\delta}$ uniquely solves the initial value problem

$$
\left\{\begin{array}{l}
\left(\partial_{t}-\mathcal{L}_{f}\right) u_{f}^{\delta}(t)=0, \quad \text { for } t>0 \\
u_{f}^{\delta}(0)=\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)
\end{array}\right.
$$

Now suppose that $h$ is a 'small perturbation' such that $f+h \in \mathcal{F}$. Then, using (A.2) and the corresponding PDE with $\mathcal{L}_{f+h}$ in place of $\mathcal{L}_{f}$, we see that the difference $u_{f+h}^{\delta}-u_{f}^{\delta}$ constitutes the (unique) solution to

$$
\left\{\begin{array}{l}
\left(\partial_{t}-\mathcal{L}_{f}\right) w(t)=\nabla \cdot\left(h \nabla u_{f+h}^{\delta}(t)\right), \quad \text { for } t>0 \\
w(0)=0
\end{array}\right.
$$

A.3. A key parabolic regularity result. We will crucially use the PDE characterisation (A.3) to derive a norm bound for $u_{f+h}^{\delta}-u_{f}^{\delta}$ (in a suitable function space). To do so, we will make extensive use of the optimal regularity theory of parabolic PDEs, e.g. [59]. For the convenience of the reader, we shall summarise some key results below - details are left to Appendix B.1.

It is well-known that $\mathcal{L}_{f}: H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O}) \rightarrow L^{2}(\mathcal{O})$ is a 'sectorial operator' in the sense that its 'resolvent set' contains a large enough sector in the complex plane $\mathbb{C}$, and that the resolvents satisfy a suitable norm estimate; see Appendix B. 1 for the precise definition. Consequently,

the transition semigroup $e^{t \mathcal{L}_{f}}$ can be interpreted using the holomorphic functional calculus. For any bounded and continuous function $g:[0, T] \rightarrow L^{2}(\mathcal{O})$ and any initial condition $u_{0} \in$ $H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})$, consider the initial value problem

$$
\begin{cases}\left(\partial_{t}-\mathcal{L}_{f}\right) u(t)=g(t), & t \in(0, T) \\ u(0)=u_{0} . & \end{cases}
$$

Then, by standard theory, laid out e.g. in Chapter 4.1. of [59], the unique solution to (A.4) is given by the variation-of-constants formula ${ }^{1}$

$$
u(t)=e^{t \mathcal{L}_{f}} u_{0}+\int_{0}^{t} e^{(t-s) \mathcal{L}_{f}} g(s) d s, \quad t \in[0, T]
$$

Thus, the regularity theory for the solutions to (A.4) reduces to the study of the above representation formula. We will also use the notation $\left(\partial_{t}-\mathcal{L}_{f}\right)^{-1}$ to denote the solution operator mapping (suitably smooth and integrable) functions $g:[0, T] \rightarrow L^{2}(\mathcal{O})$ to the solution of (A.5) with $u_{0}=0$,

$$
\left[\left(\partial_{t}-\mathcal{L}_{f}\right)^{-1} g\right](t)=\int_{0}^{t} e^{(t-s) \mathcal{L}_{f}} g(s) d s, \quad t \in[0, T]
$$

For $\alpha \in(0,1)$, let $C^{\alpha}\left([0, T] ; L^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)$ denote the space of $\alpha$-Hölder continuous functions from $[0, T]$ to $L^{2}(\mathcal{O})$. For $0<\alpha<1, \beta>0$ and $X \in\left\{L^{2}(\mathcal{O}), H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right\}$, we introduce the spaces

$$
\begin{aligned}
C_{\beta}^{\alpha}((0, T] ; X):= & \bigcap_{0<\varepsilon \leq T} C^{\alpha}([\varepsilon, T] ; X) \cap\left\{u: \sup _{0<t \leq T} t^{\beta-\alpha}\|u(t)\|_{X}<\infty\right\} \\
& \cap\left\{u: \sup _{0<\varepsilon<T} \varepsilon^{\beta}\|u\|_{C^{\alpha}([\varepsilon, T], X)}<\infty\right\}
\end{aligned}
$$

normed by

$$
\|u\|_{C_{\beta}^{u}((0, T] ; X)}:=\sup _{0<t \leq T} t^{\beta-\alpha}\|u(t)\|_{X}+\sup _{0<\varepsilon<T} \varepsilon^{\beta}\|u\|_{C^{\alpha}([\varepsilon, T] ; X)}
$$

Note that if $\beta>\alpha$ the above norm allows for $\|u(t)\|_{X}$ to blow up at polynomial rate when $t \rightarrow 0$.

The following 'optimal regularity' estimate for the solution $u$ given by the variation-ofconstants formula (A.5) is a version of Theorem 4.3.7 in [59], and is used repeatedly throughout our proofs. A more general version can be found in Theorem B. 1 below. We shall only need the case $u_{0}=0$.

THEOREM A.1. For some $\alpha, \mu \in(0,1)$, assume that $g \in C_{\alpha+\mu}^{\alpha}\left((0, T] ; L^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)$, and let $u:[0, T] \rightarrow L^{2}(\mathcal{O})$ be given by (A.5). Then, $u \in C_{\alpha+\mu}^{\alpha}\left((0, T] ; H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)$ and $\partial_{t} u \in$ $C_{\alpha+\mu}^{\alpha}\left((0, T] ; L^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)$. Moreover, there exists a constant $C>0$ (independent of $g$ ) such that

$$
\|u\|_{C_{\alpha+\mu}^{\alpha}\left((0, T] ; H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)}+\left\|\partial_{t} u\right\|_{C_{\alpha+\mu}^{\alpha}\left((0, T] ; L^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)} \leq C\|g\|_{C_{\alpha+\mu}^{\alpha}\left((0, T] ; L^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)}
$$

Informally speaking, the theorem asserts that the solution (A.5) satisfies two types of 'parabolic regularity'. Firstly, the regularity in space of $u$ is of order $H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})$ whenever the spatial smoothness of $g$ is of $L^{2}(\mathcal{O})$ type. Secondly, $u$ also possesses regularity in time, in that the smoothness of $\partial_{t} u$ matches that of $g$.

We shall not be concerned with distinguishing different notions of solution to (A.4), since all solutions considered here will constitute 'strict' solutions. This is the strongest notion of those considered in the abstract parabolic theory; see, e.g. [59].

A.4. Estimates for differences of regularised transition densities. We are now ready to use the PDE (A.3) to derive bounds for differences between regularised transition densities.

Lemma A.2. Suppose that $d \leq 3$ and that $f, h: \mathcal{O} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ are such that $f, f+h \in \mathcal{F}$, where $\mathcal{F}$ is given by (2.1). Let

$$
w_{f, h}:=u_{f+h}^{\delta}-u_{f}^{\delta}, \quad w_{f, h}:[0, T] \rightarrow L^{2}(\mathcal{O})
$$

Then, there exist some constants $\alpha \in(0,1)$ (sufficiently small), $\mu \in(0,1)$ (sufficiently large), $\gamma \in(0,1)$ as well as $C>0$ only depending on $f_{\min }, \|f\|_{C^{1}},\|h\|_{C^{1}}, \mu$ and $\gamma$ such that

$$
\left\|w_{f, h}\right\|_{C_{\alpha+\mu}^{\alpha}\left((0, T] ; H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O}))}+\left\|\partial_{t} w_{f, h}\right\|_{C_{\alpha+\mu}^{\alpha}\left((0, T] ; L^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)} \leq C\|h\|_{C^{1}} \delta^{-\gamma}
$$

The preceding bound is the main technical result of this section. It will be the key for us to employ a bootstrap argument to also control 'higher order approximations' of the transition densities; see Section A. 5 below.

Proof. Since $w_{f, h}$ satisfies the parabolic PDE (A.3), in light of Theorem A.1, it suffices to derive a regularity estimate for the inhomogeneity term in (A.3), which we shall denote by

$$
g(t) \equiv g_{f, h}^{\delta}(t):=\nabla \cdot\left(h \nabla u_{f+h}^{\delta}(t)\right), \quad g:[0, T] \rightarrow L^{2}(\mathcal{O})
$$

Our goal is to bound the $C_{\alpha+\mu}^{\alpha}\left((0, T] ; L^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)$-norm of $g$ for $\alpha$ and $\mu$ to be suitably chosen later in the proof. This is achieved in four steps; Steps 1-3 deal with estimating

$$
\sup _{\varepsilon \in(0, T]} \varepsilon^{\alpha+\mu}\|g\|_{C^{\alpha}\left([\varepsilon, T] ; L^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)}
$$

while Step 4 deals with bounding

$$
\sup _{t \in(0, T]} t^{\mu}\|g(t)\|_{L^{2}}
$$

Step 1. Fix any $\varepsilon \in(0, T)$, as well as any $\varepsilon<t^{\prime}<t \leq T$. Then, we have that

$$
\begin{aligned}
\|g(t)-g\left(t^{\prime}\right)\|_{L^{2}} & =\left\|\nabla \cdot\left(h \nabla\left(u_{f+h}^{\delta}(t)-u_{f+h}^{\delta}\left(t^{\prime}\right)\right)\right)\right\|_{L^{2}} \\
& \lesssim\|h\|_{C^{1}}\left\|u_{f+h}^{\delta}(t)-u_{f+h}^{\delta}\left(t^{\prime}\right)\right\|_{H^{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

In order to further bound the right hand side, we use the norm equivalence

$$
C^{-1}\left(\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f+h} u\right\|_{L^{2}}+\|u\|_{L^{2}}\right) \leq\|u\|_{H^{2}} \leq C\left(\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f+h} u\right\|_{L^{2}}+\|u\|_{L^{2}}\right)
$$

from Lemma B.2, holding for all $u \in H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})$ and for some $C$ that only depends on $f_{\min }$ and $\|f+h\|_{C^{1}}$. It follows that

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|u_{f+h}^{\delta}(t)\right. & \left.-u_{f+h}^{\delta}\left(t^{\prime}\right)\right\|_{H^{2}} \\
& \simeq\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f+h}\left[u_{f+h}^{\delta}(t)-u_{f+h}^{\delta}\left(t^{\prime}\right)\right]\right\|_{L^{2}}+\left\|u_{f+h}^{\delta}(t)-u_{f+h}^{\delta}\left(t^{\prime}\right)\right\|_{L^{2}} \\
& =: I+I I
\end{aligned}
$$

Step 2: Term 1. Term $I$ is the most difficult to bound among the two, and we treat it first. Denoting by $I d$ the identity operator, and using the semigroup property of $\left(P_{t, f+h}, t \geq 0\right)$, the definition of $u_{f+h}^{\delta}$ as well as the fact that $\mathcal{L}_{f+h}$ and $P_{t, f+h}$ commute, we have that

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f+h}\left[u_{f+h}^{\delta}(t)-u_{f+h}^{\delta}\left(t^{\prime}\right)\right]\right\|_{L^{2}} & =\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f+h}\left(P_{t-t^{\prime}, f+h}-I d\right)\left[P_{t^{\prime}, f+h}\left[\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right]\right]\right\|_{L^{2}} \\
& =\left\|\left(P_{t-t^{\prime}, f+h}-I d\right)\left[\mathcal{L}_{f+h} P_{t^{\prime}, f+h}\left[\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right]\right]\right\|_{L^{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Moreover, standard analytic semigroup theory implies that for some $M<\infty$ it holds that

$$
\sup _{0<t \leq T} t\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f+h} P_{t, f+h}\right\|_{L^{2} \rightarrow L^{2}} \leq M ; \quad \sup _{0<t \leq T} t\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f+h} P_{t, f+h}\right\|_{H_{N}^{2} \rightarrow H_{N}^{2}} \leq M
$$

see e.g. the estimates (2.1.1) in [59]. Above, for $X \in\left\{L^{2}(\mathcal{O}), H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right\}$, we have denoted by $\|\cdot\|_{X \rightarrow X}$ the usual operator norm. Next, for $\alpha \in(0,1)$ we denote by $\mathcal{D}_{\alpha}$ a suitable interpolation space between $L^{2}(\mathcal{O})$ and $H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})$ defined in (B.4) below. This space has norm

$$
\|u\|_{\mathcal{D}_{\alpha}}:=\|u\|_{L^{2}}+\sup _{t \in(0,1)} t^{-\alpha}\left\|P_{t, f} u-u\right\|_{L^{2}}
$$

see (B.5). Using the interpolation inequality

$$
\|u\|_{\mathcal{D}_{\alpha}} \lesssim\|u\|_{L^{2}}^{1-\alpha}\|u\|_{H^{2}}^{\alpha}, \quad u \in \mathcal{D}_{\alpha}
$$

as well (A.10), we may therefore estimate

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left\|\left(P_{t-t^{\prime}, f+h}-I d\right)\left[\mathcal{L}_{f+h} P_{t^{\prime}, f+h}\left[\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right]\right]\right\|_{L^{2}} \\
& \quad \lesssim\left(t-t^{\prime}\right)^{\alpha}\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f+h} P_{t^{\prime}, f+h}\left[\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right]\right\|_{\mathcal{D}_{\alpha}} \\
& \quad \lesssim\left(t-t^{\prime}\right)^{\alpha}\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f+h} P_{t^{\prime}, f+h}\left[\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right]\right\|_{L^{2}}^{1-\alpha}\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f+h} P_{t^{\prime}, f+h}\left[\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right]\right\|_{H^{2}}^{\alpha} \\
& \quad \lesssim\left(t-t^{\prime}\right)^{\alpha}\left(t^{\prime}\right)^{-1}\left\|\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right\|_{L^{2}}^{1-\alpha}\left\|\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right\|_{H^{2}}^{\alpha} \\
& \quad \lesssim\left(t-t^{\prime}\right)^{\alpha} \varepsilon^{-1}\left\|\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right\|_{L^{2}}^{1-\alpha}\left\|\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right\|_{H^{2}}^{\alpha}
\end{aligned}
$$

Next, we use the heat kernel estimates from Lemma B. 6 below to obtain the bound

$$
\begin{gathered}
\left(t-t^{\prime}\right)^{\alpha} \varepsilon^{-1}\left\|\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right\|_{L^{2}}^{1-\alpha}\left\|\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right\|_{H^{2}}^{\alpha} \\
\lesssim\left(t-t^{\prime}\right)^{\alpha} \varepsilon^{-1} \delta^{-(1-\alpha) d / 4} \delta^{-\alpha(d / 2+2)}=\left(t-t^{\prime}\right)^{\alpha} \varepsilon^{-1} \delta^{-\gamma}
\end{gathered}
$$

where we have set

$$
\gamma \equiv \gamma(\alpha):=(1-\alpha) d / 4+\alpha(d / 2+2)=d / 4+\alpha(2+d / 4)
$$

Since $d \leq 3$, we can (and will) choose a sufficiently small value for $\alpha>0$ to guarantee that $\gamma<1$, as required in the statement of the lemma.

Step 3: Term II; combining the estimates. Term $I I$ can be estimated similarly. Indeed, it holds that for some $M>0$,

$$
\sup _{0<t \leq T}\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f+h} P_{t, f+h}\right\|_{L^{2} \rightarrow L^{2}} \leq M ; \quad \sup _{0<t \leq T}\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f+h} P_{t, f+h}\right\|_{H_{N}^{2} \rightarrow H_{N}^{2}} \leq M
$$

Then, arguing as above, we obtain that

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|\left(P_{t-t^{\prime}, f+h}-I d\right)\left[P_{t^{\prime}, f+h}\left[\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right]\right]\right\|_{L^{2}} & \lesssim\left(t-t^{\prime}\right)^{\alpha}\left\|\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right\|_{L^{2}}^{1-\alpha}\left\|\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right\|_{H^{2}}^{\alpha} \\
& \lesssim\left(t-t^{\prime}\right)^{\alpha} \delta^{-(1-\alpha) d / 4} \delta^{-\alpha(d / 2+2)} \\
& =\left(t-t^{\prime}\right)^{\alpha} \delta^{-\gamma}
\end{aligned}
$$

Combining (A.9), (A.11) and (A.13) then implies that $\|g\|_{C^{\alpha}\left([\varepsilon, T] ; L^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)} \lesssim\|h\|_{C^{1}} \varepsilon^{-1} \delta^{-\gamma}$. Now choose any $\mu \in(1-\alpha, 1)$. For such $\mu$, we have proven that

$$
\sup _{\varepsilon \in(0, T]} \varepsilon^{\alpha+\mu}\|g\|_{C^{\alpha}\left([\varepsilon, T] ; L^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)}<\delta^{-\gamma}\|h\|_{C^{1}}
$$

Step 4. There remains to bound $\sup _{0<t \leq 1} t^{\mu}\|g(t)\|_{L^{2}}$. Arguing as before and using again the norm equivalence (A.8),

$$
\begin{aligned}
\|g(t)\|_{L^{2}} & \lesssim\|h\|_{C^{1}}\left\|P_{t, f+h}\left[\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right]\right\|_{H^{2}} \\
& \simeq\left\|P_{t, f+h} \mathcal{L}_{f+h}\left[\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right]\right\|_{L^{2}}+\left\|P_{t, f+h}\left[\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right]\right\|_{L^{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Just like in Steps I and II, we focus on the first term, as the second one is easier to control. By another application of the standard properties of analytic semigroups, it holds that for some $M<\infty$,

$$
\sup _{0<t \leq 1}\left\|P_{t, f+h} \mathcal{L}_{f+h}\right\|_{L^{2} \rightarrow L^{2}} \leq t^{-1} M ; \quad \sup _{0<t \leq 1}\left\|P_{t, f+h} \mathcal{L}_{f+h}\right\|_{H^{2} \rightarrow L^{2}} \leq M
$$

cf. eq. (2.1.1) in [59]. Using interpolation theory, e.g. Theorem 1.2.6 in [59], and by possibly changing the constant $M$, we then obtain that

$$
\sup _{0<t \leq 1}\left\|P_{t, f+h} \mathcal{L}_{f+h}\right\|_{\mathcal{D}_{\alpha} \rightarrow L^{2}} \leq t^{\alpha-1} M
$$

It follows that

$$
\left\|P_{t, f+h} \mathcal{L}_{f+h}\left[\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right]\right\|_{L^{2}} \lesssim t^{\alpha-1}\left\|\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right\|_{L^{2}}^{1-\alpha}\left\|\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right\|_{H^{2}}^{\alpha}
$$

We now may follow the same arguments as in (A.11) and (A.13) to derive the estimate,

$$
\|g(t)\|_{L^{2}} \lesssim t^{\alpha-1} \delta^{-\gamma}
$$

Choosing $\alpha$ and $\gamma$ as in (A.12), arguing as in (A.11) and using that $\mu>1-\alpha$, we then obtain that

$$
\sup _{0<t \leq T} t^{\mu}\|g(t)\|_{L^{2}} \leq \sup _{0<t \leq T} t^{\mu-(1-\alpha)}\|g(t)\|_{L^{2}} \lesssim T^{\mu-(1-\alpha)}\|h\|_{C^{1}} \delta^{-\gamma}
$$

This completes the proof of the lemma.
A.5. Higher-order approximations. One can interpret the difference $w_{f, h}=u_{f+h}^{\delta}-u_{f}^{\delta}$ as the remainder term of a 'zeroth order' (i.e. constant) approximation of the operator $\tilde{f} \mapsto u_{f}^{\delta}$ at some fixed point $f \in \mathcal{F}$. In light of this interpretation, fixing some $f \in \mathcal{F}$, we introduce the notation

$$
M_{0}^{\delta}[h](t):=u_{f}^{\delta}(t), \quad M_{0}^{\delta}[h]:[0, T] \rightarrow L^{2}(\mathcal{O})
$$

for the zeroth order approximation, and define the remainder term by

$$
R_{0}^{\delta}[h](t):=u_{f+h}^{\delta}(t)-u_{f}^{\delta}(t), \quad R_{0}^{\delta}:[0, T] \rightarrow L^{2}(\mathcal{O})
$$

While this notation may at first seem artificial, it will prove very convenient for generalisations to higher order local polynomial approximations in directions $h$ around some $f \in \mathcal{F}$, which we now define recursively. The following construction is adapted from [101].

For any $k \geq 1$ and $f, h$ as above, and recalling the solution operator (A.6), we define the $k^{\text {th }}$ order 'monomial' approximation term as

$$
M_{k}^{\delta}[h](t):=\left(\partial_{t}-\mathcal{L}_{f}\right)^{-1}\left[\nabla \cdot\left(h \nabla M_{k-1}^{\delta}[h]\right)\right](t)
$$

Naturally, since we are mostly interested in the characterisation of the first-order derivative, the most important term will be the linear one, $M_{1}^{\delta}[h]$; see Corollary A.4. The above definitions should at first be understood to be formal expressions - in the next lemma, it will be recursively shown that the terms $M_{k-1}^{\delta}[h]$ are suitably regular such that the action of the solution operator $\left(\partial_{t}-\mathcal{L}_{f}\right)^{-1}$ upon them is well-defined.

Before doing so, we note that it is clear from the recursive definition that, for all $k \geq 1$, $M_{k}^{\delta}[h]$ is homogeneous of degree $k$ in $h$. Indeed, the sum $\sum_{l=0}^{k} M_{l}^{\delta}[h]$ will serve as our 'candidate' $k^{\text {th }}$ order local polynomial approximation to the transition densities around $f$. We denote the associated remainder term by

$$
R_{k}^{\delta}[h]:=u_{f+h}^{\delta}-\sum_{l=0}^{k} M_{l}^{\delta}[h]
$$

In order to show that the approximation by $\sum_{l=0}^{k} M_{l}^{\delta}[h]$ is the correct one, we will prove that the size of $R_{k}^{\delta}[h]$ is of order at most $o\left(\|h\|_{C^{1}}^{E}\right)$. Indeed, from the definition, it is easily seen that, for each $k \geq 1, R_{k}^{\delta}[h]$ also satisfies a recursive relationship, which reads

$$
\begin{cases}\left(\partial_{t}-\mathcal{L}_{f}\right) R_{k-1}^{\delta}[h](t)=\left[\nabla \cdot\left(h \nabla R_{k-1}^{\delta}[h]\right)\right](t), & \text { for } t>0 \\ R_{k}^{\delta}[h](0)=0 . & \end{cases}
$$

Using this characterisation, we will now extend Lemma A. 2 (which established an upper bound for $R_{0}^{\delta}[h]$ ) to all $R_{k}^{\delta}[h], k \geq 1$, by induction (again, we note that the case $k=1$ will be the most important for us, but proving the estimate for all $k \geq 1$ is no more complicated than the argument for $k=1$ ).

LEMMA A.3. Suppose that $d \leq 3$ and that $f, h: \mathcal{O} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ are such that $f, f+h \in \mathcal{F}$. Then, for any $k \geq 0$, there exists a sufficiently small constant $\alpha>0$, some $\gamma \in(0,1)$ and some $C>0$ such that

$$
\left\|R_{k}^{\delta}[h]\right\|_{C_{\alpha+\mu}^{\alpha}\left((0, T] ; H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)}+\left\|\partial_{t} R_{k}^{\delta}[h]\right\|_{C_{\alpha+\mu}^{\alpha}\left((0, T] ; L^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)} \leq C\|h\|_{C^{1}}^{k+1} \delta^{-\gamma}
$$

The key implication of the preceding lemma is that it identifies the directional derivatives of the regularised transition densities. Using the lemma with $k=1$, we immediately obtain that the Frechét derivative of the regularised maps $f \in \mapsto u_{f}^{\delta}$ must be given by the operator $h \mapsto M_{\delta}^{1}[h]$. In light of this, we introduce the notation

$$
D \Phi_{f}^{\delta}[h]:=M_{1}^{\delta}[h](D)
$$

Corollary A.4. Suppose that $d \leq 3$. Then, with $\alpha, \mu, \gamma \in(0,1)$ as in Lemma A.3, we have that

$$
\left\|u_{f+h}^{\delta}-u_{f}^{\delta}-D \Phi_{f}^{\delta}[h]\right\|_{C_{\alpha+\mu}^{\alpha}\left((0, T] ; H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)}=\left\|R_{\delta}^{1}[h]\right\|_{C_{\alpha+\mu}^{\alpha}\left((0, T] ; H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)}=O\left(\delta^{-\gamma}\|h\|_{C^{1}}^{2}\right)
$$

as $h \rightarrow 0$. In particular, using the Sobolev embedding $H^{2}(\mathcal{O}) \subset C(\mathcal{O})$, it follows that for any fixed and positive $D>0$,

$$
\left\|u_{f+h}^{\delta}(D)-u_{f}^{\delta}(D)-D \Phi_{f}^{\delta}[h]\right\|_{L^{\infty}}=O\left(\delta^{-\gamma}\|h\|_{C^{1}}^{2}\right)
$$

In fact, following the arguments of [101], one could also prove that the regularised transition densities are direction-wise analytic. However, this is not needed for the algorithmic purposes of this article, and we shall omit this generalisation in order to avoid additional technicalities.

We conclude this section with the proof of Lemma A.3.
Proof of Lemma A.3. We proceed by induction on the order $k$. Induction start $k=0$. This is shown in Lemma A. 2 .

Induction step $(k-1) \rightarrow k$. Suppose now that $k \geq 1$, and that the claim holds for some $k-1$. In view of the PDE characterisation (A.15) of $R_{k}^{\delta}[h]$ and by the regularity estimate from

Theorem A.1, our proof strategy is to derive a bound for $\left\|\nabla \cdot\left(h \nabla R_{k-1}^{\delta}[h]\right)\right\|_{C_{\alpha+\mu}^{\alpha}((0, T] ; L^{2}(\mathcal{O}))}$. To this end, for each $t \in(0, T]$, we estimate

$$
\begin{aligned}
t^{\mu}\left\|\nabla \cdot\left(h \nabla R_{k-1}^{\delta}[h]\right)(t)\right\|_{L^{2}} & \lesssim t^{\mu}\|h\|_{C^{1}}\left\|R_{k-1}^{\delta}[h](t)\right\|_{H^{2}} \\
& \lesssim\|h\|_{C^{1}}\left\|R_{k-1}^{\delta}[h]\right\|_{C_{\alpha+\mu}^{\alpha}((0, T] ; H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O}))}
\end{aligned}
$$

Similarly, it holds that for any $t>t^{\prime} \geq \varepsilon>0$,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\varepsilon^{\alpha+\mu}\left\|\nabla \cdot\left(h \nabla\left[R_{k-1}^{\delta}[h]\right)(t)\right.\right. & -\nabla \cdot\left(h \nabla R_{k-1}^{\delta}[h]\right)\left(t^{\prime}\right)\left\|_{L^{2}}\right. \\
& \leq \varepsilon^{\alpha+\mu}\|h\|_{C^{1}}\left\|R_{k-1}^{\delta}[h](t)-R_{k-1}^{\delta}[h]\left(t^{\prime}\right)\right\|_{H^{2}} \\
& \leq \varepsilon^{\alpha+\mu}\|h\|_{C^{1}}\left(t-t^{\prime}\right)^{\alpha}\left\|R_{k-1}^{\delta}[h](t)\right\|_{C^{\alpha}\left(\left[\varepsilon, T\right] ; H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)} \\
& \leq\|h\|_{C^{1}}\left(t-t^{\prime}\right)^{\alpha}\left\|R_{k-1}^{\delta}[h]\right\|_{C_{\alpha+\mu}^{\alpha}\left([0, T] ; H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)}
\end{aligned}
$$

Thus, using the above two displays together with the PDE (A.15), the regularity estimate (B.1) and the induction hypothesis, we obtain

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|R_{k}^{\delta}[h]\right\|_{C_{\alpha+\mu}^{\alpha}((0, T] ; H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O}))} & +\left\|\partial_{t} R_{k}^{\delta}[h]\right\|_{C_{\alpha+\mu}^{\alpha}((0, T] ; L^{2}(\mathcal{O}))} \\
& \leq\left\|\nabla \cdot\left(h \nabla R_{k-1}^{\delta}[h]\right)\right\|_{C_{\alpha+\mu}^{\alpha}((0, T] ; L^{2}(\mathcal{O}))} \\
& \lesssim\|h\|_{C^{1}}\left\|R_{k-1}^{\delta}[h]\right\|_{C_{\alpha+\mu}^{\alpha}((0, T] ; H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O}))} \leq C\|h\|_{C^{1}}\|h\|_{C^{1}}^{k} \delta^{-\gamma}
\end{aligned}
$$

which proves the claim.
A.6. Taking the limit $\delta \rightarrow 0$. Corollary A. 4 characterises the linearisation of the regularised transition densities for fixed $\delta>0$. To prove Theorem 2.1, we need to take the limit $\delta \rightarrow 0$. Since the regularity estimates obtained in the previous section depend in a specific manner on $\delta$, this requires some care; in particular, $\delta$ will be chosen according to the size of the perturbation $h$.

Proof of Theorem 2.1. Fix $x, y \in \mathcal{O}$, and $f$ and $h$ as in the hypotheses. Our goal to show that the (unregularised) transition densities satisfy

$$
\left|p_{D, f+h}(x, y)-p_{D, f}(x, y)-D \Phi_{f}[h](x)\right|=o\left(\|h\|_{C^{1}}\right)
$$

To mirror the preceding notation, we write $u_{f}(t):=p_{t, f}(\cdot, y), t \geq 0$. Then, it suffices to show that

$$
\left\|u_{f+h}(D)-u_{f}(D)-D \Phi_{f}[h]\right\|_{L^{\infty}}=o\left(\|h\|_{C^{1}}\right)
$$

We take the 'intuitive' approach of approximating each of the above three terms with their $\delta$-regularised version, obtaining the decomposition

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|u_{f+h}(D)-u_{f}(D)-D \Phi_{f}[h]\right\|_{L^{\infty}} \leq & \left\|u_{f+h}^{\delta}(D)-u_{f+h}^{\delta}(D)-D \Phi_{f}^{\delta}[h]\right\|_{L^{\infty}} \\
& +\left\|u_{f+h}^{\delta}(D)-u_{f+h}(D)\right\|_{L^{\infty}} \\
& +\left\|u_{f}^{\delta}(D)-u_{f}(D)\right\|_{L^{\infty}}+\left\|D \Phi_{f}^{\delta}[h]-D \Phi_{f}[h]\right\|_{L^{2}} \\
= & : I+I I+I I I+I V
\end{aligned}
$$

Choice of $\delta$. We now make the crucial choice for the regularisation parameter $\delta$ in dependence of $h$. Let $\gamma \in(0,1)$ be the constant from Lemma A.3. Then, we fix some $\beta \in\left(1, \gamma^{-1}\right)$,

and set $\delta:=\|h\|_{C^{1}}^{\beta}$. For this choice of $\delta$, we will be able to show that all four terms in the preceding decomposition are of order $o\left(\|h\|_{C^{1}}\right)$.

Term $I$. The first term is exactly equal to $\left\|R_{1}^{\delta}[h](D)\right\|_{L^{\infty}}$. Thus, using Lemma A. 3 as well as the Sobolev embedding $H^{2}(\mathcal{O}) \subset C(\mathcal{O})$ (since $d \leq 3$ ), we see that for some $\alpha>0$,

$$
\begin{aligned}
I & =\left\|R_{1}^{\delta}[h](D)\right\|_{L^{\infty}} \\
& \lesssim\left\|R_{1}^{\delta}[h](D)\right\|_{H^{2}} \lesssim\left\|R_{1}^{\delta}[h]\right\|_{C_{x_{\infty}}^{x}(\{0, T\} ; H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O}))} \lesssim\|h\|_{C^{1}}^{2} \delta^{-\gamma}=\|h\|_{C^{1}}^{2-\gamma \beta}=o\left(\|h\|_{C^{1}}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

For the last identity, we used that $\beta \gamma<1$.
Term $I I$. Let us denote the transition operators of the reflected Brownian motion by $\left(P_{t}, t>0\right)$. Since $\left(P_{t}, t>0\right)$ constitutes an analytic semigroup generated by the Laplace operator acting on $C(\mathcal{O})$ with domain $C_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O}):=\left\{u \in C^{2}(\mathcal{O}): \partial_{\nu} u=0\right\}$ (see Section B.1.3 below for details), we can use the inequality (B.7) together with the assumption that $\|h\|_{C^{2}} \leq 1$ to obtain

$$
I I=\left\|\left(P_{\delta}-I d\right) u_{f+h}(D)\right\|_{C(\mathcal{O})} \lesssim \delta\left\|u_{f+h}(D)\right\|_{C_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})} \lesssim \delta\left\|u_{f+h}(D)\right\|_{C^{2+\eta}}=o\left(\|h\|_{C^{1}}\right)
$$

Here, we also used the fact that

$$
\sup _{h \in C^{2}:\|h\|_{C^{1+\eta}} \leq 1}\left\|u_{f+h}\right\|_{C^{2+\eta}}<\infty
$$

which follows from Lemma B. 7 below.
Term III. The third term can be treated in the same way as Term $I I$, with $u_{f+h}$ replaced by $u_{f}$.

Term $I V$. We further decompose

$$
\begin{aligned}
I V= & \left\|D \Phi_{f}^{\delta}[h]-D \Phi_{f}[h]\right\|_{L^{\infty}} \\
= & \left\|\int_{0}^{D} P_{D-s, f}\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}\left(p_{s, f}^{\delta}(x, \cdot)-p_{s, f}(x, \cdot)\right)\right] d s\right\|_{L^{\infty}} \\
= & \left\|\int_{0}^{D / 2} P_{D-s, f}\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}\left(p_{s, f}^{\delta}(x, \cdot)-p_{s, f}(x, \cdot)\right)\right] d s\right\|_{L^{\infty}} \\
& +\left\|\int_{D / 2}^{D} P_{D-s, f}\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}\left(p_{s, f}^{\delta}(x, \cdot)-p_{s, f}(x, \cdot)\right)\right] d s\right\|_{L^{\infty}} \\
= & : I V_{a}+I V_{b}
\end{aligned}
$$

Term $I V_{a}$. The main difficult is to deal with the singularity of $p_{s, f}$ for $s \rightarrow 0$. Using Lemma B.8, we obtain that for some $C>0$ and any $t>D / 2$,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left\|P_{t, f}\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}\left(p_{s, f}^{\delta}(x, \cdot)-p_{s, f}(x, \cdot)\right)\right]\right\|_{L^{\infty}} \leq\left\|\nabla \cdot\left(h \nabla\left(p_{s, f}^{\delta}(x, \cdot)-p_{s, f}(x, \cdot)\right)\right)\right\|_{\left(H_{N}^{2}\right)^{*}} \\
& \quad=\sup _{\varphi \in H_{N}^{2}:\|\varphi\|_{H^{2}} \leq 1}\left|\int_{\mathcal{O}}\left[\nabla \cdot\left(h \nabla\left(p_{s, f}^{\delta}(x, \cdot)-p_{s, f}(x, \cdot)\right)\right](z) \varphi(z) d z\right]\right.
\end{aligned}
$$

Using the self-adjointness of the differential operator $\nabla \cdot(h \nabla[\cdot])$, the dual characterisation of $\|\cdot\|_{L^{2}}$, (B.6) as well as Lemma B.6, for any $\eta \in(0,1 / 2)$ we can further estimate the right hand side, up to a multiplicative constant, by

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \sup _{\varphi \in H_{N}^{2}:\|\varphi\|_{H^{2}} \leq 1}\left|\int_{\mathcal{O}}\left(p_{s, f}^{\delta}(x, z)-p_{s, f}(x, z)\right)[\nabla \cdot(h \nabla \varphi)](z) d z\right| \\
& \quad \lesssim\|h\|_{C^{1}}\left\|p_{s, f}^{\delta}(x, \cdot)-p_{s, f}(x, \cdot)\right\|_{L^{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& =\|h\|_{C^{1}}\left\|\left(P_{\delta, 0}-I d\right) p_{s, f}(x, \cdot)\right\|_{L^{2}} \\
& \lesssim\|h\|_{C^{1}} \delta^{\eta}\left\|p_{s, f}(x, \cdot)\right\|_{H^{2 \eta}} \\
& \lesssim\|h\|_{C^{1}} \delta^{\eta}\left\|p_{s, f}(x, \cdot)\right\|_{L^{2}}^{1-\eta}\left\|p_{s, f}(x, \cdot)\right\|_{H^{2}}^{\eta} \lesssim\|h\|_{C^{1}} \delta^{\eta} s^{-d(1-\eta) / 4} s^{-\eta(d / 2+2)}
\end{aligned}
$$

Now let

$$
\gamma \equiv \gamma(\eta):=d(1-\eta) / 4+\eta(d / 2+2)
$$

Note that this corresponds to the exponent defined in (A.12). By choosing $\eta>0$ small enough and using the fact that $d \leq 3$, we can ensure that $\gamma<1$, so that the previous expression is integrable at $s=0$. As a consequence, for any such $\eta$, we have

$$
I V_{a} \lesssim\|h\|_{C^{1}} \delta^{\eta}=o\left(\|h\|_{C^{1}}\right)
$$

Term $I V_{b}$. We now turn to term $I V_{b}$. Here, we fix some $y \in \mathcal{O}$. Then, using the selfadjointness of $\mathcal{L}_{h}$ as well as of $P_{\delta, 0}-I d$, we obtain

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \int_{D / 2}^{D} P_{D-s, f}\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}\left(p_{s, f}^{\delta}(x, \cdot)-p_{s, f}(x, \cdot)\right)\right](y) d s \\
& =\int_{D / 2}^{D}\left\langle P_{D-s, f}(y, \cdot), \mathcal{L}_{h}\left(p_{s, f}^{\delta}(x, \cdot)-p_{s, f}(x, \cdot)\right)\right\rangle_{L^{2}} d s \\
& =\int_{D / 2}^{D}\left\langle\left(P_{\delta, 0}-I d\right) \mathcal{L}_{h}\left(P_{D-s, f}(y, \cdot)\right), p_{s, f}(x, \cdot)\right\rangle_{L^{2}} d s \\
& =\int_{D / 2}^{D} P_{s, f}\left[\left(P_{\delta, 0}-I d\right) \mathcal{L}_{h}\left(P_{D-s, f}(y, \cdot)\right)\right](x) d s \\
& =\int_{0}^{D / 2} P_{D-s, f}\left[\left(P_{\delta, 0}-I d\right) \mathcal{L}_{h}\left(p_{s, f}(y, \cdot)\right)\right](x) d s \\
& \leq \int_{0}^{D / 2}\left\|P_{D-s, f}\left[\left(P_{\delta, 0}-I d\right) \mathcal{L}_{h}\left(p_{s, f}(y, \cdot)\right)\right]\right\|_{L^{\infty}} d s .
\end{aligned}
$$

Now, we can employ a similar chain of estimates (albeit slightly more complicated) as we did for term $I V_{a}$. Another type of interpolation space between $L^{2}(\mathcal{O})$ and $H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})$, different from the previously used ones, will be useful here. We follow Chapter 1, Section 2.1 of [57]. We denote by $\left[H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O}), L^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right]_{\eta}, \eta \in[0,1]$, the interpolation spaces obtained through the construction there, defined as the domain of fractional powers $\Delta^{\eta}$ of the Neumann-Laplacian, satisfying $H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O}) \subseteq\left[H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O}), L^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right]_{\eta} \subseteq L^{2}(\mathcal{O})$. By the duality result is Theorem 6.2 of Chapter 1 in [57] and identifying $\left(L^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)=\left(L^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)^{*}$, it holds that for all $\eta \in[0,1]$,

$$
\left(\left[H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O}), L^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right]_{1-\eta}\right)^{*}=\left[L^{2}(\mathcal{O}),\left(H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)^{*}\right]_{\eta}
$$

For any $s \in[0, D]$, using Lemma B.8, we can then estimate the integrand as follows, for any $\eta \in(0,1)$,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left\|P_{D-s, f}\left[\left(P_{\delta, 0}-I d\right) \mathcal{L}_{h}\left(p_{s, f}(y, \cdot)\right)\right]\right\|_{L^{\infty}} \\
& \quad \lesssim\left\|\left(P_{\delta, 0}-I d\right) \mathcal{L}_{h}\left(p_{s, f}(y, \cdot)\right)\right\|_{\left(H_{N}^{2}\right)^{*}} \\
& \quad \lesssim \sup _{\varphi \in H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O}):\|\varphi\|_{H^{2}} \leq 1}\left|\left\langle\left(P_{\delta, 0}-I d\right) \mathcal{L}_{h}\left(p_{s, f}(y, \cdot)\right), \varphi\right\rangle_{L^{2}}\right|
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \lesssim \sup _{\varphi \in H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O}):\|\varphi\|_{H^{2}} \leq 1}\left|\left\langle p_{s, f}(y, \cdot), \mathcal{L}_{h}\left(P_{\delta, 0}-I d\right) \varphi\right\rangle_{L^{2}}\right| \\
& \lesssim\left\|p_{s, f}(y, \cdot)\right\|_{\left[H_{N}^{2}, L^{2}\right]_{\eta}} \sup _{\varphi \in H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O}):\|\varphi\|_{H^{2}} \leq 1}\left\|\mathcal{L}_{h}\left(P_{\delta, 0}-I d\right) \varphi\right\|_{\left(\left[H_{N}^{2}, L^{2}\right]_{\eta}\right)^{*}} \\
& \lesssim\left\|p_{s, f}(y, \cdot)\right\|_{H^{2}}^{\eta}\left\|p_{s, f}(y, \cdot)\right\|_{L^{2}}^{1-\eta} \sup _{\varphi \in H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O}):\|\varphi\|_{H^{2}} \leq 1}\left\|\mathcal{L}_{h}\left(P_{\delta, 0}-I d\right) \varphi\right\|_{\left[L^{2},\left(H_{N}^{2}\right)^{*}\right]_{1-\eta}}
\end{aligned}
$$

the last step holding since $\left(\left[L^{2}(\mathcal{O}), H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right]_{\eta}\right)^{*}=\left[L^{2}(\mathcal{O}),\left(H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)^{*}\right]_{1-\eta}$ (see Theorem 6.2 in [57]). Then, using Lemma A. 5 below, as well as the boundedness of $P_{\delta, 0}-I d$ as an operator from $H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})$ to itself, we see that

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|\mathcal{L}_{h}\left(P_{\delta, 0}-I d\right) \varphi\right\|_{\left(\left[L^{2}, H_{N}^{2}\right]_{\eta}\right)^{*}} & \lesssim\|h\|_{C^{1}}\left\|\left(P_{\delta, 0}-I d\right) \varphi\right\|_{\left[L^{2}, H_{N}^{2}\right]_{1-\eta}} \\
& \lesssim\|h\|_{C^{1}}\left\|\left(P_{\delta, 0}-I d\right) \varphi\right\|_{L^{2}}^{\eta}\left\|\left(P_{\delta, 0}-I d\right) \varphi\right\|_{H^{2}}^{1-\eta} \\
& \lesssim\|h\|_{C^{1}} \delta^{\eta}\|\varphi\|_{H^{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Now, we can choose $\eta>0$ small enough, just as after (A.17), such that $\gamma(\eta)<1$. Combining the preceding estimates, we obtain that

$$
\left\|P_{D-s, f}\left[\left(P_{\delta, 0}-I d\right) \mathcal{L}_{h}\left(p_{s, f}(y, \cdot)\right)\right]\right\|_{L^{\infty}} \lesssim\|h\|_{C^{1}} \delta^{\eta} s^{-\gamma}
$$

which is integrable on $s \in(0, D / 2)$. Upon integration, we have $I V_{b}=O\left(\|h\|_{C^{1}} \delta^{\eta}\right)=$ $o\left(\|h\|_{C^{1}}\right)$, and the proof is complete.

LEMMA A.5. Let $\eta \in[0,1]$. Then, there exists some $C>0$ such that for all $h \in C^{1}(\mathcal{O})$ and all $u \in H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})$,

$$
\left\|\mathcal{L}_{h} u\right\|_{\left[L^{2},\left(H_{N}^{2}\right)^{*}\right]_{1-\eta}} \leq C\|h\|_{C^{1}}\|u\|_{\left[H_{N}^{2}, L^{2}\right]_{\eta}}
$$

Proof. Clearly, $\mathcal{L}_{h}: H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O}) \rightarrow L^{2}(\mathcal{O})$ is bounded and satisfies, for any $u \in H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})$,

$$
\left\|\mathcal{L}_{h} u\right\|_{L^{2}}=\|\nabla \cdot(h \nabla u)\|_{L^{2}} \lesssim\|h\|_{C^{1}}\|u\|_{H^{2}}
$$

Using a standard duality argument, we then obtain that for some $C>0$, for any $u \in H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})$,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|\mathcal{L}_{h} u\right\|_{\left(H_{N}^{2}\right)^{*}} & =\sup _{\varphi \in H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O}):\|\varphi\|_{H^{2}} \leq 1}\left|\int_{\mathcal{O}} \varphi(x) \mathcal{L}_{h} u(x) d x\right| \\
& =\sup _{\varphi \in H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O}):\|\varphi\|_{H^{2}} \leq 1}\left|\int_{\mathcal{O}} u(x) \mathcal{L}_{h} \varphi(x) d x\right| \\
& \leq C \sup _{\varphi \in L^{2}(\mathcal{O}):\|\varphi\|_{L^{2}} \leq 1}\left|\int u(x) \varphi(x) d x\right|=C\|u\|_{L^{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Following the argument of the Theorem 5.1 in [57], we then see that for all $u \in H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})$,

$$
\left\|\mathcal{L}_{h} u\right\|_{\left[L^{2},\left(H_{N}^{2}\right)^{*}\right]_{\eta}} \lesssim\|u\|_{\left[H_{N}^{2}, L^{2}\right]_{\eta}}
$$

But at the same time, by (A.18), we have that $\left[L^{2}(\mathcal{O}),\left(H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right)^{*}\right]_{\eta}=\left[H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O}), L^{2}(\mathcal{O})\right]_{1-\eta}$, completing the proof.

# APPENDIX B: AUXILIARY TECHNICAL RESULTS ON PARABOLIC EQUATIONS AND HEAT KERNELS 

We review some basic definitions and facts about analytic semigroups, which constitute some crucial technical tools in the proofs of our main results.

B.1. Background on parabolic PDEs. A key idea underpinning the analysis to follow is to interpret a collection of transition operators $\left(P_{t}, t \geq 0\right)$ as an analytic semigroup generated by a so-called 'sectorial' operator $\mathcal{L}$. This allows to study the regularity properties of the solutions to abstract Cauchy problems of the form

$$
\left\{\begin{array}{l}
\partial_{t} u(t)=\mathcal{L} u(t)+g(t), \quad t \in(0, T) \\
u(0)=u_{0}
\end{array}\right.
$$

Naturally, in our setting, the relevant operator is given by the infinitesimal generator $\mathcal{L}_{f}$ of the diffusion process (1.3).
B.1.1. Sectorial operators and analytic semigroups. We follow the presentation in the monograph by Lunardi [59]. Let $X$ be a complex Banach space, and suppose that $\mathcal{L}: \mathcal{D}(\mathcal{L}) \rightarrow$ $X$ is a linear operator with domain $\mathcal{D}(\mathcal{L}) \subseteq X$, constituting a (not necessarily densely defined) subspace of $X$. Heuristically, $\mathcal{L}$ is called a sectorial operator if its resolvent set $\rho(\mathcal{L}) \subseteq \mathbb{C}$ contains a 'sector', and if the resolvents $R(\lambda, \mathcal{L}), \lambda \in \rho(\mathcal{L})$, satisfy a certain decay. In particular, $\mathcal{L}$ is sectorial if there exist constants $\omega \in \mathbb{R}, \theta \in(\pi / 2, \pi)$, and $M>0$ such that

$$
\rho(\mathcal{L}) \supset S_{\theta, \omega}:=\{\lambda \in \mathbb{C}: \lambda \neq \omega,|\arg (\lambda-\omega)|<\theta\}
$$

and, denoting by $\|\cdot\|_{X \rightarrow X}$ the usual operator norm,

$$
\|R(\lambda, \mathcal{L})\|_{X \rightarrow X} \leq \frac{M}{|\lambda-\omega|}, \quad \forall \lambda \in S_{\theta, \omega}
$$

It turns out that sectoriality is sufficient to that the operator exponentials $\left(e^{t \mathcal{L}}, t>0\right)$ are well-defined via functional calculus. They then form the analytic semigroup

$$
\left(P_{t}, t \geq 0\right), \quad P_{t}:=e^{t \mathcal{L}}
$$

in the sense that the map $t \mapsto P_{t}$ is analytic.
B.1.2. Characterisation of $\mathcal{D}(\mathcal{L})$ and interpolation spaces. The domain $\mathcal{D}(\mathcal{L})$ of the sectorial operator $\mathcal{L}$ is naturally equipped with the graph norm

$$
\|u\|_{\mathcal{D}(\mathcal{L})}:=\|u\|_{X}+\|\mathcal{L} u\|_{X}, \quad u \in \mathcal{D}(\mathcal{L})
$$

Moreover, the behaviour of the map $t \mapsto e^{t \mathcal{L}} u$ at $t=0$ characterises the domain $\mathcal{D}(\mathcal{L})$. Namely, it holds that $\lim _{t \rightarrow 0}\left(e^{t \mathcal{L}} u-u\right) / t$ exists (as a limit in $X$ ) and equals $\mathcal{L} u$ if and only if $u \in \mathcal{D}(\mathcal{L})$ and $\mathcal{L} u \in \overline{\mathcal{D}(\mathcal{L})}$. As an consequence, for every $u \in \mathcal{D}(\mathcal{L})$ with $\mathcal{L} u \in \overline{\mathcal{D}(\mathcal{L})}$, an alternative characterisation of the graph norm of $u$ is

$$
\|u\|_{\mathcal{D}(\mathcal{L})} \simeq\|u\|_{X}+\sup _{0<t \leq 1} t^{-1}\left\|e^{t \mathcal{L}} u-u\right\|_{X}
$$

One can similarly define certain interpolation spaces $\mathcal{D}_{\alpha}$, for $\alpha \in(0,1)$, between $X$ and $\mathcal{D}(\mathcal{L})$, which are of importance in the proofs. Specifically, set

$$
\mathcal{D}_{\alpha}:=\left\{u \in X: \sup _{t \in(0,1]} t^{-\alpha}\left\|e^{t \mathcal{L}} u-u\right\|_{X}<\infty\right\}
$$

which is equipped with norm

$$
\|u\|_{\mathcal{D}_{\alpha}}:=\|u\|_{X}+\sup _{t \in(0,1]} t^{-\alpha}\left\|e^{t \mathcal{L}} u-u\right\|_{X}
$$

We refer to Section 2.2.1 and Proposition 2.2.4 in [59] for further details on the interpretation of these spaces - note that our spaces $\mathcal{D}_{\alpha}$ correspond to the spaces $D_{\mathcal{L}}(\alpha)=(X, \mathcal{D}(\mathcal{L}))_{\alpha}$ from [59]. The above interpolation can be defined for instance via the ' K -method'; see the display (1.2.4) in [59].

B.1.3. The case $\mathcal{L}=\mathcal{L}_{f}$. For our purposes, the relevant instance is the transition semigroup $\left(P_{t, f}, t \geq 0\right)$ of the reflected diffusion process (1.3), with associated (elliptic) infinitesimal generator $\mathcal{L}_{f}[\cdot]=\nabla \cdot(f \nabla[\cdot])$ equipped with zero Neumann boundary conditions. Two different realisations of the operator $\mathcal{L}_{f}$ will play a role, firstly viewed as an operator on the Hilbert space $X=L^{2}(\mathcal{O})$ with domain

$$
H_{N}^{2}(\overline{\mathcal{O}})=\left\{u \in H^{2}(\mathcal{O}): \partial_{\nu} u=0 \text { on } \partial \mathcal{O}\right\}
$$

and secondly as an operator on the Banach space $X=C(\overline{\mathcal{O}})$ with domain $C_{N}^{2}(\overline{\mathcal{O}})$ defined similarly to $H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})$. It is well-known that $\mathcal{L}_{f}$ forms a sectorial operator on both spaces. Indeed, on $L^{2}(\mathcal{O})$, this follows from Theorems 3.1.2 and 3.1.3 in [59], where the main tool for the verification of the resolvent bounds (B.2) are the a-priori estimates by Agmon-DouglisNirenberg [2]. On $C(\overline{\mathcal{O}})$, similar resolvent bounds can be verified; see Section 3.1.5, and especially Corollary 3.1.24 (ii), in [59]. We also note that the zero Neumann boundary conditions imposed here satisfy the non-tangentiality condition (3.1.3) in [59], since

$$
\inf _{x \in \partial \mathcal{O}}\left|\sum_{i=1}^{n} \nu_{i}^{2}(x)\right|=\inf _{x \in \partial \mathcal{O}}|\nu(x)|=1>0
$$

The equations (B.3) and (B.5) then directly yield useful characterisations of Sobolev- and Hölder-type norms in terms of the behaviour of $P_{t, f} u-u$, which we use throughout. Specifically, we note that for any $u \in H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O}), f \in \mathcal{F}$ and $\alpha \in[0,1]$, it holds that

$$
\left\|P_{t, f} u-u\right\|_{L^{2}} \lesssim t^{\alpha}\|u\|_{H^{2 \alpha}}, \quad t \in(0,1)
$$

Similarly, for $u \in C_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})$,

$$
\left\|P_{t, f} u-u\right\|_{L^{\infty}} \lesssim t\|u\|_{C^{2}}, \quad t \in(0,1)
$$

B.1.4. Regularity estimates for parabolic PDEs. We now provide an overview on some key regularity results for the parabolic PDE (B.1). A variety of notions of solutions to such equations exists in the literature. Since, via the regularisation argument developed in Section A, we only need to consider a sequence of parabolic PDEs with regularised initial conditions, the strongest of these notions will suffice for our purposes: thus, when we speak of a solution to the Cauchy problem (B.1), we mean a strict solution in the sense that for all $t \in[0, T]$, $\partial_{t} u(t)=\mathcal{L} u(t)+g(t)$ and $u(0)=u_{0}$.

When $g:[0, T] \rightarrow X$ is continuous, one then shows that any (strict) solution to (B.1) must necessarily be given by the variation-of-constants formula

$$
u(t)=e^{t \mathcal{L}} u_{0}(t)+\int_{0}^{t} e^{(t-s) \mathcal{L}} g(s) d s, \quad 0 \leq t \leq T
$$

where the integral on the right hand side is in the Bochner sense; see Proposition 4.1.2 in [59]. For our purposes, this property is always fulfilled.

Turning to the regularity of the solutions to the Cauchy problem (B.1), the following (scales of) function spaces are needed: firstly, for $\alpha \in(0,1)$, let $C^{\alpha}([0, T] ; X)$ be the set of $\alpha$-Hölder continuous functions from $[0, T]$ to $X$. Secondly, we introduce spaces that allow for certain singularities at $t=0$ - this is central for the proofs in Section A, as it enables to derive regularity estimates that are uniform with respect to the regularisation parameter introduced there. For $0<\alpha<1$ and $\beta>0$, set

$$
\begin{aligned}
C_{\beta}^{\alpha}((0, T] ; X):= & \bigcap_{0<z \leq T} C^{\alpha}([\varepsilon, T] ; X) \cap\left\{u: \sup _{0<t \leq T} t^{\beta-\alpha}\|u(t)\|_{X}<\infty\right\} \\
& \cap\left\{u: \sup _{0<z<T} \varepsilon^{\beta}\|u\|_{C^{\alpha}([\varepsilon, T], X)}<\infty\right\}
\end{aligned}
$$

The following result is deduced from Theorem 4.3.1 (iii) and Theorem 4.3.7 in [59]. Since we shall only deal with the case $u_{0}=0$, let

$$
u(t)=\int_{0}^{t} e^{(t-s) \mathcal{L}} g(s) d s
$$

THEOREM B.1. (i) Suppose that $g \in C^{\alpha}([0, T] ; X)$ for some $\alpha \in(0,1)$, and let $g(0) \in$ $\mathcal{D}(\mathcal{L})$. Then, $u$ in (B.8) constitutes a strict solution to the Cauchy problem (B.1). Furthermore, $u \in C^{\alpha}([0, T] ; D(\mathcal{L})) \cap C^{1+\alpha}([0, T] ; X)$.
(ii) Suppose additionally that $g \in C_{n+\mu}^{\alpha}((0, T] ; X)$ for some $\alpha, \mu \in(0,1)$. Then, there exists $C>0$ (independent of $g$ ) such that

$$
\|u\|_{C_{n+\mu}^{\alpha}((0, T] ; \mathcal{D}(\mathcal{L}))}+\left\|\partial_{t} u\right\|_{C_{n+\mu}^{\alpha}((0, T] ; X)} \leq C\|g\|_{C_{n+\mu}^{\alpha}((0, T] ; X)}
$$

B.2. Estimates for elliptic second order differential operators. The proofs in Section A also require a number of estimates for the solutions of elliptic PDEs, both in $L^{2}$-type norms and in uniform norms. We begin providing the estimates for the former. The first result is a basic lemma concerning the equivalence of the graph norm of $\mathcal{L}_{f}$, for $f$ belonging to the parameter space $\mathcal{F}$ from (2.1), and the $H^{2}(\mathcal{O})$-norm.

LEMMA B.2. Let $R>0$. There exists a constant $C>0$ only depending on $f_{\min }, R$ and $\mathcal{O}$ such that for all $f \in \mathcal{F}$ with $\|f\|_{C^{1}} \leq R$, and all $u \in H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})$,

$$
C^{-1}\|u\|_{H^{2}} \leq\|u\|_{L^{2}}+\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f} u\right\|_{L^{2}} \leq C\|u\|_{H^{2}}
$$

Proof. To prove the second inequality, we estimate

$$
\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f} u\right\|_{L^{2}}=\|f \Delta u+\nabla f \cdot \nabla u\|_{L^{2}} \lesssim\|f\|_{L^{\infty}}\|\Delta u\|_{L^{2}}+\|f\|_{C^{1}}\|\nabla u\|_{L^{2}} \lesssim R\|u\|_{H^{2}}
$$

Thus, it remains to show the first inequality. For that, it suffices to prove that $\|\Delta u\|_{L^{2}} \leq$ $C\left(\|u\|_{L^{2}}+\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f} u\right\|_{L^{2}}\right)$ for some $C>0$ only depending on $f_{\min }, R$ and $\mathcal{O}$. To this end, we use the definition of $\mathcal{L}_{f}$, the interpolation inequality

$$
\|\nabla u\|_{L^{2}} \lesssim\|u\|_{L^{2}}^{1 / 2}\|u\|_{H^{2}}^{1 / 2} \lesssim\|u\|_{L^{2}}+\|u\|_{L^{2}}^{1 / 2}\|\Delta u\|_{L^{2}}^{1 / 2}
$$

as well as Cauchy's inequality with $\varepsilon>0$, to obtain that for some universal constants $c, c^{\prime}>0$, and for $\varepsilon \in(0,1]$,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\|\Delta u\|_{L^{2}} & =\left\|f^{-1}\left(\mathcal{L}_{f} u-\nabla f \cdot \nabla u\right)\right\|_{L^{2}} \\
& \leq f_{\min }^{-1}\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f} u\right\|_{L^{2}}+f_{\min }^{-1}\|\nabla f \cdot \nabla u\|_{L^{2}} \\
& \leq f_{\min }^{-1}\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f} u\right\|_{L^{2}}+c f_{\min }^{-1}\|f\|_{C^{1}}\left(\|u\|_{L^{2}}+\|u\|_{L^{2}}^{1 / 2}\|\Delta u\|_{L^{2}}^{1 / 2}\right) \\
& \leq f_{\min }^{-1}\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f} u\right\|_{L^{2}}+c^{\prime} f_{\min }^{-1}\|f\|_{C^{1}}\left(\frac{\|u\|_{L^{2}}}{2 \varepsilon}+\frac{\varepsilon\|\Delta u\|_{L^{2}}}{2}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Now, choosing $\varepsilon>0$ small enough and subtracting the term containing $\Delta u$ on the right hand side, we obtain that for some $C>0$ only depending on $f_{\min }, R$ and $\mathcal{O}$,

$$
\frac{1}{2}\|\Delta u\|_{L^{2}} \leq C\left(\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f} u\right\|_{L^{2}}+\|u\|_{L^{2}}\right)
$$

as desired. This concludes the proof of the lemma.
Next, we study the analogous mapping properties of $\mathcal{L}_{f}$ with respect to the Hölder spaces $C^{2+\eta}(\mathcal{O})$ and $C^{\eta}(\mathcal{O})$ for $\eta \in(0,1)$. Define

$$
C_{N}^{2+\eta}(\mathcal{O}):=\left\{u \in C^{2+\eta}(\mathcal{O}): \partial_{\nu} u=0 \text { on } \partial \mathcal{O}\right\}
$$

LEMMA B.3. Suppose that $f \in \mathcal{F}$. For any $\eta \in(0,1)$, there exists $C>0$ only depending on $\|f\|_{C^{1+\eta}}, f_{\min }$ and $\mathcal{O}$ such that for all $u \in C_{N}^{2+\eta}(\mathcal{O})$,

$$
C^{-1}\|u\|_{C^{2+\eta}} \leq\|u\|_{C^{\eta}}+\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f} u\right\|_{C^{\eta}} \leq C\|u\|_{C^{2+\eta}}
$$

Proof. Throughout, we will use the fact that for $\eta \in(0,1)$, the spaces $C^{\eta}(\mathcal{O})$ and $C^{2+\eta}(\mathcal{O})$ equal the Hölder-Zygmund spaces $\mathcal{C}^{\eta}(\mathcal{O})$ and $\mathcal{C}^{2+\eta}(\mathcal{O})$, with equivalent norms (see e.g. [93] for definitions). For these, we have the classical multiplication inequalities

$$
\|u v\|_{\mathcal{C}^{\alpha}} \lesssim\|u\|_{\mathcal{C}^{\alpha}}\|v\|_{\mathcal{C}^{\alpha}}, \quad u, v \in \mathcal{C}^{\alpha}(\mathcal{O}), \quad \alpha \geq 0
$$

The second inequality in the statement of the lemma then follows from the estimate

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f} u\right\|_{\mathcal{C}^{\eta}} & =\|f \Delta u+\nabla f \cdot \nabla u\|_{\mathcal{C}^{\eta}} \\
& \lesssim\|f\|_{\mathcal{C}^{\eta}}\|\Delta u\|_{\mathcal{C}^{2+\eta}}+\|f\|_{\mathcal{C}^{1+\eta}}\|\nabla u\|_{\mathcal{C}^{1+\eta}} \lesssim\|f\|_{\mathcal{C}^{1+\eta}}\|u\|_{\mathcal{C}^{2+\eta}}
\end{aligned}
$$

For the first inequality, we use the fact that the Laplace operator establishes (jointly with the trace operator $\operatorname{Tr}[·]$ ) a topological isomorphism

$$
u \mapsto(\Delta u, \operatorname{Tr}[u]), \quad(\Delta, \operatorname{Tr}): \mathcal{C}_{N}^{\alpha+2}(\mathcal{O}) \rightarrow \mathcal{C}^{\alpha}(\mathcal{O}) \times \mathcal{C}^{\alpha+2}(\partial \mathcal{O})
$$

for any $\alpha \geq 0$; see, for instance, Theorem 4.3.4 in [93] or also display (5.6) in [68]. Moreover, we note that by the chain rule, for any $f \in \mathcal{F}$, since $f \geq f_{\min }$, it holds that

$$
\left\|f^{-1}\right\|_{C^{1}} \lesssim\|f\|_{C^{1}}
$$

where the multiplicative constant only depends on $f_{\min }$. Using this, we obtain

$$
\begin{aligned}
\|u\|_{\mathcal{C}^{2+\eta}} & \lesssim\|\Delta u\|_{\mathcal{C}^{\eta}}+\|u\|_{\mathcal{C}^{\eta}} \\
& =\left\|f^{-1}\left(\mathcal{L}_{f} u-\nabla f \cdot \nabla u\right)\right\|_{\mathcal{C}^{\eta}}+\|u\|_{C^{\eta}} \\
& \lesssim\left\|f^{-1}\right\|_{C^{1}}\left(\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f} u\right\|_{\mathcal{C}^{\eta}}+\|f\|_{\mathcal{C}^{1+\eta}}\|u\|_{\mathcal{C}^{1+\eta}}\right)+\|u\|_{C^{\eta}} \\
& \lesssim\|f\|_{C^{1}}\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f} u\right\|_{\mathcal{C}^{\eta}}+\|f\|_{C^{1}}\|f\|_{\mathcal{C}^{1+\eta}}\|u\|_{\mathcal{C}^{\eta}}^{1 / 2}\|u\|_{\mathcal{C}^{2+\eta}}^{1 / 2}+\|u\|_{\mathcal{C}^{\eta}} \\
& \leq\|f\|_{C^{1}}\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f} u\right\|_{\mathcal{C}^{\eta}}+\|f\|_{C^{1}}\|f\|_{\mathcal{C}^{1+\eta}}\left(\frac{1}{2 \varepsilon}\|u\|_{\mathcal{C}^{\eta}}+\frac{\varepsilon}{2}\|u\|_{\mathcal{C}^{2+\eta}}\right)+\|u\|_{\mathcal{C}^{\eta}}
\end{aligned}
$$

for any $\varepsilon>0$, where we used in the last step that $a b \leq a^{2} /(2 \varepsilon)+\varepsilon b^{2} / 2$ for any $a, b \in \mathbb{R}$. Thus, choosing $\varepsilon>0$ large enough (only depending on $f_{\min },\|f\|_{\mathcal{C}^{1+\eta}}$ and $\mathcal{O}$ ) and subsequently subtracting the term in the right hand side containing $\|u\|_{\mathcal{C}^{2+\eta}}$, we have proved as desired that

$$
\|u\|_{\mathcal{C}^{2+\eta}} \lesssim\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f} u\right\|_{\mathcal{C}^{\eta}}+\|u\|_{\mathcal{C}^{\eta}}
$$

Next, we state and prove the following lemma which entails that the constants in Weyl's asymptotics for the eigenvalues of $\mathcal{L}_{f}$ can be controlled by terms that only depends on upper and lower bounds for the conductivity function $f$.

LEMMA B.4. There exists a constant $C>0$ only depending $f_{\min },\|f\|_{L^{\infty}}$ and $\mathcal{O}$ such that the eigenvalues $\left(\lambda_{f, j}, j \geq 0\right)$ of the operator $-\mathcal{L}_{f}$ with domain $\mathcal{D}\left(\mathcal{L}_{f}\right)=H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})$, ordered increasingly, satisfy

$$
C^{-1} j^{2 / d} \leq \lambda_{f, j} \leq C j^{2 / d}
$$

Proof. Let the action of the quadratic form associated to $-\mathcal{L}_{f}$ on functions $u \in H^{1}(\mathcal{O})$ be denoted by

$$
Q_{f}(u)=-\left\langle u, \mathcal{L}_{f} u\right\rangle=\int_{\mathcal{O}} f(x)|\nabla u(x)|^{2} d x
$$

For any finite-dimensional subspace $L \subseteq \mathcal{D}\left(\mathcal{L}_{f}\right)$, define

$$
\lambda_{f, j}(L):=\sup _{u \in L:\|u\|_{L^{2}} \leq 1} Q_{f}(u)
$$

We use the standard 'minimax' characterisation of the eigenvalues via minimising the above quantity over all subspaces of dimension $j$ :

$$
\lambda_{f, j}=\inf _{L \subseteq \mathcal{D}\left(\mathcal{L}_{f}\right): \operatorname{dim}(L)=j} \lambda_{f, j}(L)
$$

Now let us denote the eigenvalues of the Neumann-Laplace operator $-\Delta=\mathcal{L}_{1}$ by $\lambda_{j}=\lambda_{1, j}$, with associated quadratic form $Q_{\Delta}(u)=\int_{\mathcal{O}}|u(x)|^{2} d x$. Using Weyl's law, it holds that for some constant $c \equiv c(\mathcal{O}) \geq 1$, we have $\lambda_{j} \in\left[c^{-1} j^{2 / d}, c j^{2 / d}\right]$. It then follows immediately form the above 'variational' characterisation of the eigenvalues that there is a further constant $c^{\prime} \equiv c^{\prime}\left(f_{\min },\|f\|_{L^{\infty}}\right)>0$ for which

$$
\lambda_{f, j} \in\left[\left(c^{\prime}\right)^{-1} \lambda_{j}, c^{\prime} \lambda_{j}\right]=\left[C^{-1} j^{2 / d}, C j^{2 / d}\right]
$$

with $C \equiv C\left(f_{\min },\|f\|_{L^{\infty}}, \mathcal{O}\right)>0$, concluding the proof.
We conclude this section with a lemma on the growth of Sobolev- and Hölder norms of the eigenfunctions $e_{f, j}$, which follow straightforwardly from the previous lemmas in this section.

Lemma B.5. Let $d \leq 3, R>0$ and $\eta \in(0,1)$. There exists a constant $C>0$ only depending on $f_{\min }, R, \mathcal{O}$ and $\eta$ such that the following holds true.
i) For all $f \in \mathcal{F}$ with $\|f\|_{C^{1}} \leq R$ and all $j \geq 0,\left\|e_{f, j}\right\|_{H^{2}} \leq C\left(1+j^{2 / d}\right)$.
ii) For all $f \in \mathcal{F}$ with $\|f\|_{C^{1+\eta}} \leq R$ and all $j \geq 0,\left\|e_{f, j}\right\|_{C^{2+\eta}} \leq C\left(1+j^{5 / d}\right)$.

Proof. Part i) follows from an application of Lemma B. 2 and B.4, which together imply

$$
\left\|e_{f, j}\right\|_{H^{2}} \simeq\left\|e_{f, j}\right\|_{L^{2}}+\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f} e_{f, j}\right\|_{L^{2}} \lesssim 1+j^{2 / d}
$$

Note that the implicit constants, by Lemmas B. 2 and B.4, only depend on the relevant quantities in the statement.

To prove part ii), we use Lemma B.3, the classical interpolation inequality for Hölder spaces (see, e.g., Corollary 1.2.19 from [59]), the Sobolev embedding, Lemma B. 4 as well as the first part of this lemma, to estimate

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|e_{f, j}\right\|_{C^{2+\eta}} & \simeq\left\|e_{f, j}\right\|_{C^{\eta}}+\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f} e_{f, j}\right\|_{C^{\eta}} \\
& \lesssim\left(1+\lambda_{f, j}\right)\left\|e_{f, j}\right\|_{C^{\eta}} \\
& \lesssim\left(1+\lambda_{f, j}\right)\left\|e_{f, j}\right\|_{L^{\infty}}^{2 /(2+\eta)}\left\|e_{f, j}\right\|_{C^{2+\eta}}^{\eta /(2+\eta)} \\
& \lesssim\left(1+j^{2 / d}\right)\left\|e_{f, j}\right\|_{H^{2}}^{2 /(2+\eta)}\left\|e_{f, j}\right\|_{C^{2+\eta}}^{\eta /(2+\eta)} \\
& \lesssim\left(1+j^{2 / d}\right)^{1+2 /(2+\eta)}\left\|e_{f, j}\right\|_{C^{2+\eta}}^{\eta /(2+\eta)}
\end{aligned}
$$

The statement follows from dividing both sides by $\left\|e_{f, j}\right\|_{C^{2+\eta}}^{\eta /(2+\eta)}$ and noting that $\eta<1$.

B.3. Estimates for the Neumann heat kernel. We now turn to deriving estimates for the Neumann heat kernels $p_{t, f}$. Again, we start with $L^{2}$-type bounds.

Lemma B.6. Let $p_{t, f}$ denote the heat kernel (i.e. the transition density function) of the reflected diffusion process (1.3). For all $f \in \mathcal{F}$, there exists a constant $C>0$ only depending on $f_{\min },\|f\|_{L^{\infty}}$ and $\mathcal{O}$, such that

$$
\sup _{y \in \mathcal{O}}\left\|p_{t, f}(\cdot, y)\right\|_{L^{2}} \leq C t^{-d / 4}, \quad t>0
$$

Moreover, for $d \leq 3$ we also have that for some constant $C \equiv C(\mathcal{O})>0$,

$$
\sup _{y \in \mathcal{O}}\left\|p_{t, f}(\cdot, y)\right\|_{H^{2}} \leq C t^{-d / 2-2}, \quad t>0
$$

In particular, the heat kernel $\varphi_{\delta}$ of the reflected standard Brownian motion on $\mathcal{O}$ (corresponding to the case $f=1$ ) satisfies

$$
\sup _{y \in \mathcal{O}}\left\|\varphi_{\delta}(\cdot, y)\right\|_{L^{2}} \leq C \delta^{-d / 4}, \quad \delta>0
$$

Proof. We first note that by the classical Gaussian estimates for the Neumann heat kernel (e.g. [29])

$$
p_{t, f}(x, y) \leq C t^{-d / 2} \exp \left(-\frac{\|x-y\|^{2}}{C t}\right)
$$

for some $C$ only depending on $f_{\min }$ and $\|f\|_{L^{\infty}}$. Then,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|p_{t, f}(\cdot, y)\right\|_{L^{2}}^{2} & \lesssim \int_{\mathcal{O}} t^{-d} \exp \left(-\frac{2\|x-y\|^{2}}{C t}\right) d x \\
& \leq t^{-d / 2} \int_{\mathcal{O}} t^{-d / 2} \exp \left(-\frac{2\|x-y\|^{2}}{C t}\right) d x \lesssim t^{-d / 2}
\end{aligned}
$$

proving the first claim. For the estimate in $H^{2}(\mathcal{O})$, assume that $d \leq 3$. Using the spectral decomposition

$$
p_{t, f}(x, y)=\sum_{j=0}^{\infty} e^{-\lambda_{f, j} t} e_{f, j}(x) e_{f, j}(y), \quad t>0, \quad x, y \in \mathcal{O}
$$

Then, using the Sobolev embedding and Lemmas B. 4 and B.5, it follows that for some $c>0$,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|p_{t, f}(\cdot, y)\right\|_{H^{2}} & \leq \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} e^{-\lambda_{f, j} t}\left\|e_{f, j}\right\|_{H^{2}}\left|e_{f, j}(y)\right| \\
& \lesssim \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} e^{-c j^{-2 / d} t}\left\|e_{f, j}\right\|_{H^{2}}^{2} \simeq \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} e^{-c j^{-2 / d} t}\left(1+j^{4 / d}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

which is further upper bounded by

$$
\begin{aligned}
\int_{0}^{\infty} e^{-c j^{2 / d} t}\left(1+j^{4 / d}\right) d j & =\int_{0}^{\infty} e^{-c x^{2}}\left(1+x^{d} t^{-d / 2}\right)^{4 / d} x^{d-1} t^{-d / 2} d x \\
& \lesssim t^{-d / 2}+t^{-d / 2-2}
\end{aligned}
$$

which proves the second claim.

Next, we derive the following uniform estimate.

LEMMA B.7. Let $\eta \in(0,1), D>0$ and $R>0$. Then, there exists $C \equiv C\left(D, R, f_{\min }\right)>0$ such that for every $f \in \mathcal{F}$ with $\|f\|_{C^{1+\eta}} \leq R$ and for every $y \in \mathcal{O}$,

$$
\left\|p_{D, f}(\cdot, y)\right\|_{C^{2+\eta}} \leq C
$$

Proof. Let us fix $y \in \mathcal{O}$ and $f$ as in the statement. Recall the notation $u_{f}(D)=$ $p_{D, f}(\cdot, y)$. Then, using the spectral decomposition, the preceding estimates as well as Lemmas B. 4 and B.5, we see that for some constants $c, C>0$ (only depending on $D, R, f_{\min }, \eta$ and $\mathcal{O})$

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|u_{f}(D)\right\|_{C^{2+\eta}} & \leq \sup _{y \in \mathcal{O}} \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} e^{-D \lambda_{f, j}}\left\|e_{f, j}\right\|_{C^{2+\eta}}\left|e_{f, j}(y)\right| \\
& \leq \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} e^{-D \lambda_{f, j}}\left\|e_{f, j}\right\|_{C^{2+\eta}}\left\|e_{f, j}\right\|_{L^{\infty}} \\
& \lesssim \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} e^{-D \lambda_{f, j}}\left\|e_{f, j}\right\|_{C^{2+\eta}}\left\|e_{f, j}\right\|_{H^{2}} \lesssim \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} e^{-c D j^{2 / d}}\left(1+j^{5 / d}\right)\left(1+j^{2 / d}\right) \lesssim C
\end{aligned}
$$

Alongside the above upper bounds, we record the following lower bound for the Neumann heat kernel, holding uniformly over balls of Hölder spaces - see Proposition 4 in [64]. In particular, if $\|f\|_{C^{\alpha}} \leq B$ for some even integer $\alpha>d / 2-1$ and some $B>0$, then for every $t>0$

$$
\inf _{x, y \in \mathcal{O}} p_{t, f}(x, y) \geq C
$$

for a constant $C \equiv C\left(t, \mathcal{O}, d, f_{\min }, B, \alpha\right)>0$.
Finally, we conclude with a uniform estimate for the action of the transition operator $P_{t, f}$ over functions in $L^{2}(\mathcal{O})$.

LEMMA B.8. Suppose that $d \leq 3$. Then, for any $D_{0}>0$ and $R>0$ there exist constants $C, C^{\prime}>0$ only depending on $D_{0}, R, f_{\min }$, and $\mathcal{O}$ such that for all $t \geq D_{0}$ and all $f \in \mathcal{F}$ with $\|f\|_{C^{1}} \leq R, P_{t}: L^{2}(\mathcal{O}) \rightarrow L^{\infty}(\mathcal{O})$ is a bounded linear operator satisfying

$$
\left\|P_{t, f} \varphi\right\|_{L^{\infty}} \leq C\left\|P_{t, f} \varphi\right\|_{H^{2}} \leq C^{\prime}\|\varphi\|_{\left(H_{N}^{2}\right)^{*}}, \quad \forall \varphi \in L^{2}(\mathcal{O})
$$

Proof. The first inequality is simply an application of the Sobolev embedding. To prove the second, we first note that $P_{t, f}: L^{2}(\mathcal{O}) \rightarrow \mathcal{D}\left(\mathcal{L}_{f}\right)=H_{N}^{2}(\mathcal{O})$ is linear and bounded, with operator norm only depending on $D_{0}, R, f_{\min }$, and $\mathcal{O}$. This is seen by applying the previous lemmas in this section, and by using Parseval's identity (twice), to the effect that

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|P_{t, f} \varphi\right\|_{H^{2}}^{2} & \simeq\left\|P_{t, f} \varphi\right\|_{L^{2}}^{2}+\left\|\mathcal{L}_{f} P_{t, f} \varphi\right\|_{L^{2}}^{2} \\
& \leq\|\varphi\|_{L^{2}}^{2}+\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\left|\left\langle e_{f, j}, \varphi\right\rangle_{L^{2}}\right|^{2} \lambda_{f, j}^{2} e^{-2 t \lambda_{f, j}} \lesssim\|\varphi\|_{L^{2}}^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Now, applying this twice with $t / 2$ (which is still lower bounded by $D_{0} / 2$ ) instead of $t$, and using the self-adjointness of $P_{f, t / 2}$, we obtain that

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|P_{t, f} \varphi\right\|_{H^{2}} & \leq\left\|P_{f, t / 2} \varphi\right\|_{L^{2}} \\
& =\sup _{\phi \in L^{2}(\mathcal{O}):\|\phi\|_{L^{2}} \leq 1}\left|\int_{\mathcal{O}} \phi(x) P_{f, t / 2} \varphi(x) d x\right| \\
& =\sup _{\phi \in L^{2}(\mathcal{O}):\|\phi\|_{L^{2}} \leq 1}\left|\int_{\mathcal{O}} \varphi(x) P_{f, t / 2} \phi(x) d x\right| \\
& \lesssim \sup _{\phi \in H_{N}^{e}(\mathcal{O}):\|\phi\|_{H^{2}} \leq 1}\left|\int_{\mathcal{O}} \phi(x) \varphi(x) d x\right|=\|\varphi\|_{\left(H_{N}^{e}\right)^{*}}
\end{aligned}
$$

C.3. Stationary Gaussian process priors. Alongside the random series expansions on orthonormal bases considered in the previous sections, a popular alternative approach to construct Gaussian priors on function spaces defined on $d$-dimensional domains, $d \in \mathbb{N}$, is through the specification of a stationary covariance kernel, namely a symmetric and positive semidefinite function $C: \mathbb{R}^{d} \times \mathbb{R}^{d} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ such that $C(x, y)=C(x+z, y+z)$ for all $x, y, z \in \mathbb{R}^{d}$; see Chapter 4 in [77]. A widely used choice is the Matérn kernel,

$$
C_{\mathrm{MAT}}(x, y):=\frac{2^{1-\alpha}}{\Gamma(\alpha)}\left(\frac{|x-y| \sqrt{2 \alpha}}{\ell}\right)^{\alpha} B_{\alpha}\left(\frac{|x-y| \sqrt{2 \alpha}}{\ell}\right)
$$

where $\Gamma$ is the Gamma function, $B_{\alpha}$ denotes a modified Bessel function of the second kind, and $\alpha, \ell>0$ are hyper-parameters governing the regularity and the length-scale, respectively (cf. Figure 6). A second example of interest is the squared exponential kernel,

$$
C_{\mathrm{SE}}(x, y):=e^{-|x-y|^{2} /\left(2 \ell^{2}\right)}
$$

corresponding to the limit of the Matérn one when $\alpha \rightarrow \infty$.

All the schemes were initialised with cold starts. The obtained results are summarised in Table 5 and visualised in Figure 9. The computation times were in line with those of the experiments presented in the previous sections.

abstract:
We consider the problem of making nonparametric inference in a class of
multi-dimensional diffusions in divergence form, from low-frequency data.
Statistical analysis in this setting is notoriously challenging due to the
intractability of the likelihood and its gradient, and computational methods
have thus far largely resorted to expensive simulation-based techniques. In
this article, we propose a new computational approach which is motivated by PDE
theory and is built around the characterisation of the transition densities as
solutions of the associated heat (Fokker-Planck) equation. Employing optimal
regularity results from the theory of parabolic PDEs, we prove a novel
characterisation for the gradient of the likelihood. Using these developments,
for the nonlinear inverse problem of recovering the diffusivity, we then show
that the numerical evaluation of the likelihood and its gradient can be reduced
to standard elliptic eigenvalue problems, solvable by powerful finite element
methods. This enables the efficient implementation of a large class of popular
statistical algorithms, including (i) preconditioned Crank-Nicolson and
Langevin-type methods for posterior sampling, and (ii) gradient-based descent
optimisation schemes to compute maximum likelihood and maximum-a-posteriori
estimates. We showcase the effectiveness of these methods via extensive
simulation studies in a nonparametric Bayesian model with Gaussian process
priors, in which both the proposed optimisation and sampling schemes provide
good numerical recovery. The reproducible code is available online at
https://github.com/MattGiord/LF-Diffusion.
